For readers outside Wales: In Welsh, twp means \"dustete\", and pwp means \"bish\".
A representative of the Wales party Plaid Cymru said that the group in its entirety was \"dissatisfied\" and that they have proposed alternatives.
A representative of the Welsh part of the Conservative Party said his group was \"open\" for the name change, but noted that the pronunciation of MWP is very close to the word \"Muppet\", which as well as being the name of some famous dolls, is also a British slang word for \"dust\".
In this context, the Welsh letter W is pronounced in a similar manner to the letter U is pronounced in the English Yorkshire dialect, more like an \"uh\" sound.
The Assembly Commission, which is currently developing laws to introduce the name change, said: “Of course, it is the members themselves who have the latest right of determination in relation to the name with which they are to be referred to.”
The Government of Wales Act 2017 authorized the Welsh National Assembly to change its own name.
In June, the Commission published the results of a public consultation showing public support to rename the National Assembly of the Welsh Parliament.
As regards the representatives' title, the Commission supported WMPs (Welsh Parliament Members), but the MWP option received the most support during the public consultation.
The representatives apparently propose other alternatives, but to have all parties reach an agreement may lead to a head breach for President Elin Jones, who is scheduled to deliver a legislative draft for the name change in the next couple of weeks.
The legislation on the reform will include other changes in the functioning of the National Assembly, including rules on disqualification of representatives and the design of the committee system.
Representatives have the last right to vote on what to call them when they debate the legislation.
