The study of researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as brown-lancing and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at important locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Experts’ sound analyses of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bats and what species do what.
Then a habitat map and a report will be prepared to create a detailed landscape image of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, conservation adviser for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will be included in the decision on the measures to be introduced, such as planting pastures and how to best preserve the forest for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has fallen significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction work that affects breeding sites and cutting habitats.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, the same with fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials as well as attacks from head taxes.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because of their nightly hunting habits, they have more use for the ears than the eyes when it comes to capturing prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and obstacles on the road when flying.
NTS, responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten skilled experts who regularly conduct surveys, mapping breeding sites, and sometimes rescue work.
The organization has also established Scotland's first and only own bat reserve at the Three Land Real Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bats.
David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
“Here on Three we have a perfect area for bats,” he said.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive.”
He emphasizes the importance of mapping the bats before maintaining on a property since the accidental destruction of a single breeding site can kill up to 400 females and young people, and perhaps excavate an entire local population.
The bat is protected, and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disrupt them or destroy their breeding grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish co-worker for the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help in the work.
She says: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species, we simply don’t know how the populations are doing.”
