Update on algae bloom: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Commission on Fisheries and Animal Life (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to FWC, stained blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County, suggesting reduced concentrations.
A flowering of red algae stretches about 210 km along the coast, from north of Pinellas to south of Lee County.
There are spots around 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer places than last week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
It has been reported of medium concentrations at or off the coast of Pinellas County over the past week, making high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
It is still reported of irritation in the airways of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
There was no mention of irritation in the north-west of Florida during the last week.
